==English==
===Etymology===
'''canard''' is a French word meaning [[duck]] (see below).  It has been suggested that there was a French phrase "to half-sell a duck" which meant to [[fool]] or [[cheat]] someone.
===Noun===
'''canard''' (''plural'' '''canards''')

#A [[deliberately]] false story.
#A a type of aircraft in which the primary vertical control surface is in front of the main wing.

====Quotations====
*'''2005''': It’s a cinch, now that Spurling has cleared away a century’s worth of misapprehensions and '''canards'''. &mdash; ''The New Yorker'', 29 August 2005, page 78.
----

